<DOC><DOCNO> AP890219-0104 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-89 2302EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-HostageTribute     02-19 0201</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Hostage Tribute,0207</SECOND><HEAD>Relatives Of Lebanon Hostages Attend Candlelight Tribute</HEAD><DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Relatives of American and British hostagesheld in Lebanon lit candles Sunday night to honor the captives andappeal for their release.   About 100 people attended the tribute at Calvary MissionaryChurch, including seven relatives of the hostages.   Candles were lit for each of the nine American hostages stillbelieved held in Lebanon and a photo of each captive was displayed,said Ernest May, chairman of the ``Second Annual Tribute andRecognition.''   The church's pastor sounded a message of hope to the hostages'families, May said.   In attendance Sunday night were John Anderson, brother ofAssociated Press journalist Terry Anderson; Thomas Cicippio, brotherof hostage Joseph Cicippio; Estelle Ronneburg, mother of hostageJesse Turner; Dorothy and John Rose, mother- and father-in-law ofhostage Alann Steen; and Elaine and David Collett, wife and son ofBritish hostage Alec Collett.   Other Americans believed held hostage in Lebanon are ThomasSutherland, Frank Reed, Edward Tracy, Robert Pothill and U.S. MarineLt. Col. Richard Higgins.   Sunday night's tribute was part of a two-day event organized byMay and the Bicentennial of the Constitution Committee of Pontiac,just north of Detroit.</TEXT></DOC>